"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Jeremiah 25–27 (fill script)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-jeremiah-25-27-fill.py

Ch 25: Cup of Wrath oracle — Christ as the one who drinks the cup so others need not;
       Nebuchadnezzar as servant; the seventy-year countdown to Daniel's 70 weeks;
       the divine lion who roars in judgment and is also the slain Lamb (Rev 5:5).
Ch 26: Temple Sermon trial — the most direct narrative parallel to Jesus's own trial;
       Jeremiah's "I am in your hands" (26:14) and "innocent blood" (26:15) match
       the Passion narrative almost phrase for phrase.
Ch 27: The Yoke Sign-Act — Christ's "my yoke is easy" (Matt 11:29-30) as the answer
       to Jeremiah's iron yoke; the Creator's authority given to Christ (Matt 28:18);
       Christ as the great intercessor for the temple vessels.

Key Christological nodes:
- 25:15 the cup of wrath → Matt 26:39; Mark 14:36
- 25:30-31 divine roar / all-flesh judgment → John 5:22-27; Rev 5:5
- 26:11 "deserves to die" → Matt 26:66 exact parallel
- 26:14 "I am in your hands" → Isa 53:7; John 18:11
- 26:15 "innocent blood" → Matt 27:4, 24
- 27:2 the yoke → Matt 11:28-30
- 27:18 intercessory prophets → Heb 7:25
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JEREMIAH = {
"25": {
"1": "<p>The fourth year of Jehoiakim (605/604 BC) — the year Nebuchadnezzar defeated Egypt at Carchemish and became master of the Near East. It is also the year of Daniel&apos;s first deportation (Dan 1:1). The convergence of dates links Jeremiah&apos;s great cup-of-wrath oracle with the beginning of Daniel&apos;s prophetic career in Babylon — the two prophets whose work together forms the chronological skeleton of the exile. Christ as the fulfiller of both prophecy streams enters history precisely at the end of their seventy-year and seventy-weeks countdowns (Dan 9:24-27; Luke 3:23).</p>",
"2": "<p>Jeremiah as the prophet who speaks to all Judah — the comprehensive audience of the oracle. Jesus likewise addresses all Jerusalem in his final temple discourses (Matt 23-25), culminating in the same predictions of catastrophe. The prophet who must speak to the whole people even when they do not listen is the prototype of Christ, the final prophet (Deut 18:15-18; Heb 1:1-2), whose words go out to all people even when many reject them.</p>",
"3": "<p>&quot;Twenty-three years the word of the LORD has come to me and I have spoken.&quot; The long faithfulness of the prophet — speaking without visible fruit for two decades. Hebrews 11:36-38 describes those who suffered through faithfulness, &quot;of whom the world was not worthy.&quot; Christ&apos;s own ministry of three and a half years, in which the majority rejected him, inherits and concentrates this pattern of faithful speaking to the unhearing. His ministry was not measured by acceptance but by obedience to the one who sent him (John 12:49).</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>The persistent-sending formula:</strong> &quot;the LORD has persistently sent you all his servants the prophets.&quot; <em>Hashkem v&apos;shaleach</em> — rising early and sending — is Jeremiah&apos;s signature phrase for YHWH&apos;s persistent patience. Hebrews 1:1-2 is the direct theological commentary on this verse: &quot;In the past God spoke to our ancestors through the prophets at many times and in various ways, but in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son.&quot; Christ is the Son sent as the final, definitive word after all the prophetic sendings have been rejected.</p>",
"5": "<p>&quot;Turn back from your evil way and live in the land.&quot; The covenant call to repentance with the promise of remaining in the land. Jesus&apos;s first proclamation (Mark 1:15 — &quot;repent and believe the good news&quot;) is structurally identical to this: the call to turn back, now with the kingdom of God as what the turning-back enables inhabiting. Where the land was the covenant blessing in Jeremiah, in Christ the &quot;land&quot; expands to encompass the new creation that repentance opens onto (Rom 4:13 — Abraham and his offspring inherit the <em>world</em>).</p>",
"6": "<p>&quot;Do not follow other gods... and do not provoke me to anger.&quot; The prohibition against idolatry as the center of the covenant. Paul&apos;s treatment of idolatry in Romans 1:18-25 and 1 Corinthians 10:14-22 is the NT explication of this warning. Christ enters this framework as the one who perfectly did not follow other gods — the temptation narratives (Matt 4:8-10 — &quot;worship the Lord your God and serve him only&quot;) show him refusing the idolatrous shortcut and maintaining exclusive covenant loyalty throughout.</p>",
"7": "<p>&quot;You have not listened to me and have provoked me to anger with what your hands have made.&quot; The verdict of covenant failure — the idols of human manufacture versus the God who made human hands. Acts 17:24-25 (Paul at Athens): &quot;the God who made the world and everything in it... is not served by human hands, as if he needed anything.&quot; Christ is YHWH in human hands making not idols but the healing and reconciliation that human hands could never achieve on their own (John 1:14 — the Word made flesh).</p>",
"8": "<p>&quot;Because you have not obeyed my words.&quot; The therefore-clause that introduces the judgment. Romans 5:19 — &quot;through the disobedience of the one man the many were made sinners.&quot; But the second half of the verse is the gospel: &quot;through the obedience of the one man the many will be made righteous.&quot; The judgment that falls because of disobedience (Jer 25:8) is met by the obedience of Christ that creates a new righteousness for all who are in him. The &quot;because you have not obeyed&quot; is answered by his &quot;because he obeyed.&quot;</p>",
"9": "<p>&quot;I am going to summon all the peoples of the north and Nebuchadnezzar my servant.&quot; The designation of a pagan king as YHWH&apos;s servant is theologically striking — it asserts divine sovereignty over all nations, not just Israel. Romans 13:1 (&quot;there is no authority except that which God has established&quot;) and Revelation 17:17 (&quot;God has put it into their hearts to accomplish his purpose&quot;) extend this principle. Christ is the ultimate <em>servant</em> (ebed / doulos) in whom this pattern culminates — not a pagan instrument but the willing, fully obedient Son who gives himself (Phil 2:7-8).</p>",
"10": "<p>&quot;I will silence among them the sounds of joy and gladness, the voice of the bridegroom and the bride, the grinding of millstones.&quot; The silencing of ordinary life — joy, marriage, daily work. Revelation 18:22-23 quotes this verse almost verbatim in the lament over Babylon&apos;s fall: &quot;the sound of harpists and musicians... will never be heard in you again... the voice of the bridegroom and bride will never be heard in you again.&quot; What Jeremiah pronounces against Jerusalem, Revelation declares against Babylon — but both are reversed by Christ&apos;s own wedding feast (Rev 19:7-9) where the bridegroom&apos;s voice is heard forever.</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>&quot;These nations will serve the king of Babylon for seventy years.&quot;</strong> The seventy-year exile-clock that Daniel reads as he seeks YHWH&apos;s face (Dan 9:2). Daniel&apos;s prayer (Dan 9:3-19) generates the angel&apos;s response: seventy weeks are decreed for your people — the prophecy of the 490 years that culminates in the anointed one being cut off (Dan 9:26). Christ arrives at the exact terminus of Daniel&apos;s recalculation of Jeremiah&apos;s seventy years. Jeremiah 25:11 sets the clock; Christ is its appointed hour.</p>",
"12": "<p>&quot;When seventy years are over, I will punish the king of Babylon.&quot; The accountability of the instrument of judgment — even YHWH&apos;s tools are judged for how they carry out their task. Revelation 18 is the extended fulfillment of the judgment on Babylon that Jeremiah 25:12 and chapters 50-51 announce. Christ presides over this final judgment: Revelation 19:11-16 — the rider on the white horse whose name is &quot;the Word of God&quot; executes the judgment that Jeremiah prophesied and Revelation completes.</p>",
"13": "<p>&quot;All that is recorded in this book, which Jeremiah prophesied against all the nations.&quot; The written prophecy as the permanent record against which history is measured. 2 Peter 3:7 (&quot;the present heavens and earth are reserved for fire, kept for the day of judgment&quot;) and Revelation 20:12 (&quot;the books were opened&quot;) place Christ at the center of the final accounting against which all written prophecy finds its vindication. The scroll of Jeremiah 25:13 becomes the opened books of the final assize that Christ presides over.</p>",
"14": "<p>&quot;Many nations and great kings will enslave them in turn, and I will repay them.&quot; The reciprocity of divine justice — what Babylon did to others will be done to Babylon. Galatians 6:7 — &quot;God cannot be mocked. A man reaps what he sows.&quot; Christ himself teaches this in the parable of the unmerciful servant (Matt 18:21-35) — the one who was forgiven much and forgave nothing receives the same treatment they meted out. Divine repayment is not vindictiveness but the moral coherence of the universe Christ died to restore.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>&quot;Take this cup of the wine of wrath from my hand, and make all the nations to whom I send you drink it.&quot;</strong> The cup of divine wrath — the most direct OT antecedent to Gethsemane. Matthew 26:39 — &quot;My Father, if it is possible, may this cup be taken from me.&quot; Mark 14:36 — &quot;Father, everything is possible for you. Take this cup from me. Yet not what I will, but what you will.&quot; The cup that Jeremiah is commanded to carry to all nations is the cup Christ takes into himself. Isaiah 51:17-23 promises that the cup will pass from Zion; it passes to Christ, who drinks it to the dregs (John 18:11 — &quot;Shall I not drink the cup the Father has given me?&quot;).</p>",
"16": "<p>&quot;They will drink and reel and go out of their minds because of the sword I am sending among them.&quot; The effect of drinking the cup — disorientation and destruction. Christ drank the cup and in doing so absorbed its disorienting power: the cry of desolation (Matt 27:46 — &quot;My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?&quot;) is the moment of maximum cup-drinking, the nadir of wrath absorbed. He experienced the reeling so that those who drink the new-covenant cup of his blood (1 Cor 11:25-26) receive not wrath but the Lord&apos;s death proclaimed until he comes.</p>",
"17": "<p>&quot;So I took the cup from the LORD&apos;s hand and made all the nations drink it.&quot; Jeremiah&apos;s obedience — the prophet who carries and presents the cup of judgment. Christ carries the cup one step further: not just to the nations but into himself. He is both the prophet who presents the cup (as Jeremiah) and the one who drinks it himself (as the Lamb). John 1:29 — &quot;the Lamb of God who takes away the sin of the world&quot; — the sin-bearing is the cup-drinking, now applied to all nations.</p>",
"18": "<p>Jerusalem and the cities of Judah as the first to receive the cup. &quot;It is time for judgment to begin with God&apos;s household&quot; (1 Pet 4:17) — the same principle that YHWH begins with his own people. The cross occurred in Jerusalem — judgment began where the covenant was centered. Christ died in the city that first received the cup in Jeremiah&apos;s vision, bearing the judgment that the city had accumulated through centuries of covenant violation.</p>",
"19": "<p>Pharaoh king of Egypt named among the cup-recipients. The exodus from Egypt that defined Israel&apos;s identity is now inverted: Egypt&apos;s king must drink alongside Judah&apos;s king. The great power that once held God&apos;s people captive now faces the same divine judgment as those it once enslaved. Christ&apos;s redemption creates a new exodus (Luke 9:31 — his &quot;departure&quot; / exodos is discussed at the transfiguration) that transcends the political boundaries of Jeremiah&apos;s cup-list.</p>",
"20": "<p>The foreign peoples, the land of Uz (Job&apos;s homeland), Philistia — the cup extends to the nations at Israel&apos;s borders. Romans 3:9 — &quot;both Jews and Gentiles alike are all under the power of sin.&quot; The cup-list of Jer 25:19-26 is the OT prototype of Paul&apos;s universal indictment: all are under judgment and therefore all are eligible for the universal salvation Christ provides. The comprehensiveness of the cup-list matches the comprehensiveness of the gospel invitation.</p>",
"21": "<p>Edom, Moab, and the Ammonites — the eastern neighbors, descendants of Esau and Lot. Numbers typically associated with Israel&apos;s historical enemies and occasional allies. The cup crosses kinship lines: these nations share Abraham&apos;s lineage in various ways (Edom from Esau; Moab and Ammon from Lot) but must still drink. The universal judgment that disregards ethnic connection anticipates the universal gospel that equally disregards it: Galatians 3:28 — &quot;neither Jew nor Gentile... for you are all one in Christ Jesus.&quot;</p>",
"22": "<p>Tyre and Sidon — the Phoenician trading cities whose prosperity was legendary. Jesus uses Tyre and Sidon as comparators in his judgment-speech: Matthew 11:21-22 — &quot;if the miracles performed in you had been performed in Tyre and Sidon, they would have repented long ago.&quot; The cities that were spared fuller judgment in Jeremiah&apos;s vision become in Jesus&apos;s discourse the benchmark against which Capernaum&apos;s greater refusal is measured. Christ uses the cup-list nations to calibrate the severity of rejecting him.</p>",
"23": "<p>Dedan, Tema, Buz — the Arabian trade-route peoples. The cup extends into the heart of the Arabian desert. Isaiah 21:13-17 also addresses the Arabian peoples in oracles of judgment. The geographic completeness of the cup-list (from Egypt to Media to Arabia) reflects the universal scope of divine sovereignty. Revelation 14:6-7 — &quot;an angel flying in midair, with the eternal gospel to proclaim to those who live on the earth — to every nation, tribe, language, and people&quot; — the proclamation to all has the same geographic comprehensiveness as Jeremiah&apos;s cup-list.</p>",
"24": "<p>The kings of Arabia and &quot;the various peoples who live in the desert.&quot; No human sovereignty escapes the cup — even the nomadic desert peoples who seem beyond the reach of settled kingdoms are included. Revelation 7:9 — &quot;a great multitude that no one could count, from every nation, tribe, people, and language&quot; — the peoples drawn from the desert and the margins in Jeremiah&apos;s cup-judgment appear in Revelation&apos;s vision as the redeemed from every nation standing before the throne.</p>",
"25": "<p>Elam and Media — the eastern empires that would later overthrow Babylon. They too drink the cup they will later administer to others. The irony is theological: even the destroyers of Babylon are themselves under divine judgment. No instrument of YHWH&apos;s justice escapes the scrutiny that it applies to others. Romans 2:1 — &quot;you who pass judgment on someone else are condemning yourself, because you who pass judgment do the same things.&quot; Christ alone judges without being himself under judgment (John 8:46 — &quot;Can any of you prove me guilty of sin?&quot;).</p>",
"26": "<p>&quot;All the kingdoms on the face of the earth — and last of all, the king of Sheshak will drink it.&quot; Sheshak is the atbash cipher for Babylon (š-š-k = b-b-l reversed) — the cryptographic naming of the empire that controls the world. Revelation 17-18 takes up this Babylon-mystery with full elaboration: &quot;Babylon the Great, the mother of prostitutes... the great city that rules over the kings of the earth.&quot; Christ&apos;s judgment of Babylon (Rev 19:2 — &quot;he has condemned the great prostitute&quot;) is the fulfillment of the Sheshak cup-judgment Jeremiah encodes.</p>",
"27": "<p>&quot;Drink, get drunk and vomit; fall down and never rise again.&quot; The comprehensive devastation of those who drink the cup of wrath to the end. At Gethsemane Christ prays &quot;let this cup pass from me&quot; (Matt 26:39) — this is the cup he is asking about, the cup that causes falling-and-not-rising. He does not refuse it. He drinks it fully on the cross. Isaiah 51:22-23 promises that &quot;never again will you drink it&quot; — the cup that made Zion fall has passed to another. The one who drank it rose: the resurrection is the reversal of the cup&apos;s falling-and-not-rising.</p>",
"28": "<p>&quot;If they refuse to take the cup from your hand to drink, say to them: You must certainly drink.&quot; The divine insistence on universal accountability — there is no opt-out from divine judgment. 2 Corinthians 5:10 — &quot;we must all appear before the judgment seat of Christ, so that each of us may receive what is due us for the things done while in the body.&quot; Those who refuse the cup-of-judgment from Jeremiah&apos;s hand have not escaped it — they face the same Christ at the judgment seat that Jeremiah&apos;s oracle announces for all nations.</p>",
"29": "<p><strong>&quot;I am already beginning to bring disaster on the city that bears my own name — do you think you will escape judgment? You will not go unpunished.&quot;</strong> The logic of Jeremiah&apos;s universalism: if YHWH judges even the city that carries his name, no one escapes on the grounds of proximity to him. Romans 2:9-11 — &quot;there will be trouble and distress for every human being who does evil — first for the Jew, then for the Gentile... for God does not show favoritism.&quot; Christ does not grant exemption to the covenant insiders; his judgment at the temple (&quot;not one stone will be left on another&quot;) is the enacted form of Jer 25:29.</p>",
"30": "<p><strong>&quot;The LORD will roar from on high; from his holy dwelling he will thunder.&quot;</strong> The divine roar from Zion — echoed in Joel 3:16 and Amos 1:2. Revelation 5:5 — &quot;do not weep! See, the Lion of the tribe of Judah, the Root of David, has triumphed.&quot; Christ is simultaneously the Lion who roars in judgment (Jer 25:30; Amos 1:2) and the Lamb who was slain (Rev 5:6). The two images exist in perfect tension in Revelation&apos;s throne-room vision: the roaring-lion power of Jer 25:30 is expressed through the slaughtered lamb&apos;s sacrifice. The shout of judgment is also the shout of the winepress-treader (Rev 19:15).</p>",
"31": "<p><strong>&quot;He is entering into judgment with all flesh; the wicked he will put to the sword.&quot;</strong> The global judgment: <em>kol-bāśār</em> — all flesh. John 5:22-27 — &quot;the Father judges no one, but has entrusted all judgment to the Son... for he is the Son of Man.&quot; The judgment of all flesh that YHWH announces in Jer 25:31 is given to Christ. Acts 17:31 — &quot;he has set a day when he will judge the world with justice by the man he has appointed.&quot; The &quot;all flesh&quot; scope of Jeremiah&apos;s oracle becomes the &quot;all people&quot; scope of the final judgment with Christ as judge.</p>",
"32": "<p>&quot;Disaster is spreading from nation to nation, and a great storm is rising from the far ends of the earth.&quot; The global reach of divine judgment — no geography is exempt. Matthew 24:14 — &quot;this gospel of the kingdom will be preached in the whole world as a testimony to all nations, and then the end will come.&quot; The storm-from-the-ends-of-the-earth that Jeremiah announces as judgment and the gospel-to-the-ends-of-the-earth that Jesus announces as salvation share the same geographical comprehensiveness. Both are unstoppable and universal; the difference is what they carry.</p>",
"33": "<p>&quot;Those killed by the LORD on that day will stretch from one end of the earth to the other. No one will mourn them, no one will gather them, no one will bury them.&quot; The eschatological slaughter — the scale defying normal grief-practices. Revelation 19:17-21 depicts the same scene as the battle of Armageddon: &quot;an angel standing in the sun who cried in a loud voice to all the birds flying in midair, &apos;Come, gather together for the great supper of God.&apos;&quot; Christ is the presider over this final day, not its victim. He who was left unburied (no permanent tomb — he rose) presides over the final accounting of the unburied dead.</p>",
"34": "<p>&quot;Wail, you shepherds, and cry out! Roll in the dust, you leaders of the flock! For the time of your slaughter has arrived.&quot; The shepherds who destroyed rather than tended must now face the flock&apos;s fate themselves. Ezekiel 34 is the extended meditation on this — the bad shepherds who scatter the flock. Christ&apos;s answer is John 10:11 — &quot;I am the good shepherd who lays down his life for the sheep.&quot; He does the opposite of the wailing shepherds: they flee from their own slaughter; he stays and accepts his. The shepherd-judgment of Jer 25:34 is the dark background against which the good-shepherd christology of John 10 shines.</p>",
"35": "<p>&quot;The shepherds will have nowhere to flee, and the leaders of the flock no way to escape.&quot; The inescapability of judgment for those who abused their leadership. Hebrews 2:3 — &quot;how shall we escape if we ignore so great a salvation?&quot; The question inverts Jeremiah&apos;s judgment-logic: it is not &quot;how will the wicked shepherds escape?&quot; but &quot;how will those who ignore Christ&apos;s salvation escape?&quot; Christ himself has no flight from the cross (Mark 14:41-42 — &quot;the hour has come; the Son of Man is delivered into the hands of sinners. Rise! Let us go!&quot;) — he stays while the disciples flee.</p>",
"36": "<p>&quot;The cry of the shepherds, the wailing of the leaders of the flock — for the LORD is devastating their pasture.&quot; The reversal of pastoral blessing: the pasture that the good shepherd tends has been ravaged by the bad shepherd&apos;s negligence. John 10:10 — &quot;the thief comes only to steal and kill and destroy; I came that they may have life and have it abundantly.&quot; The devastated pasture of Jer 25:36 is the aftermath of the hireling-shepherd&apos;s failure; Christ&apos;s &quot;abundant life&quot; is the restoration of the pasture to its intended fruitfulness.</p>",
"37": "<p>&quot;The peaceful grazing lands are laid waste because of the LORD&apos;s fierce anger.&quot; The <em>nāwôt haššālôm</em> — the peaceable pastures — destroyed. Psalm 23:2 — &quot;he makes me lie down in green pastures.&quot; The good shepherd restores what the fierce-anger judgment destroys. Christ as the shepherd who leads to still waters (Ps 23) and the shepherd-king of Ezekiel 34:23-24 (&quot;I will place over them one shepherd, my servant David&quot;) is the answer to the devastated-pasture oracle of Jer 25:37. The peaceable pastures are restored in the eschatological shepherd-reign of the Son of David.</p>",
"38": "<p>&quot;Like a lion he has left his den, for their land has become a desolation.&quot; YHWH as the lion who has left — the protective divine presence withdrawn, the land left to desolation. Christ&apos;s coming is the return of the protective presence: Matthew 28:20 — &quot;surely I am with you always, to the very end of the age.&quot; The lion who left the den in judgment comes back as the Lion of Judah (Rev 5:5) who establishes his permanent presence in the new Jerusalem (Rev 21:3 — &quot;God&apos;s dwelling place is now among the people&quot;). The divine absence of Jer 25:38 is answered by the permanent divine presence of Christ&apos;s new covenant.</p>"
},
"26": {
"1": "<p>The beginning of Jehoiakim&apos;s reign — the same king who burned Jeremiah&apos;s scroll (Jer 36). The dating links the temple-sermon trial narrative to a regime of active hostility to the prophetic word. Jesus operates under the same structural hostility: Luke 13:31 (&quot;leave this place, because Herod wants to kill you&quot;) and John 11:53 (&quot;from that day on, they plotted to take his life&quot;). Both prophets deliver their most dangerous messages knowing the political climate has already decided against them.</p>",
"2": "<p>&quot;Stand in the court of the LORD&apos;s temple and speak to all the people from the cities of Judah — do not omit a single word.&quot; The command to full disclosure — no softening, no omitting. Jesus teaches in the temple courts daily (Luke 19:47; 21:37) and likewise declares &quot;I have spoken openly to the world&quot; (John 18:20 — &quot;I always taught in synagogues or at the temple, where all the Jews come together. I said nothing in secret&quot;). The prophet commanded to hide nothing in the temple foreshadows the prophet-king who taught the full truth publicly from the same courts.</p>",
"3": "<p>&quot;Perhaps they will listen and turn from their evil way. Then I can relent.&quot; The divine &quot;perhaps&quot; — the genuine openness of divine repentance-response. 2 Peter 3:9 — &quot;the Lord is not slow in keeping his promise... he is patient with you, not wanting anyone to perish, but everyone to come to repentance.&quot; Christ&apos;s weeping over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41-44) is the incarnate form of the divine &quot;perhaps&quot;: the open possibility of repentance that was not taken. &quot;How often I have longed to gather your children together... but you were not willing&quot; (Matt 23:37) — the &quot;perhaps&quot; of Jer 26:3 came to personal expression in Christ&apos;s grief.</p>",
"4": "<p>&quot;If you will not listen to me, if you will not walk in my law.&quot; The conditional structure of the warning — the outcome depends on response. Matthew 23:37-38 — &quot;O Jerusalem, Jerusalem... look, your house is left to you desolate.&quot; Jesus&apos;s final temple address is the conditional of Jer 26:4-6 brought to its term: the condition was not met, the desolation follows. His pronouncement is not vindictive but the logical consequence of the covenant structure Jeremiah articulates here.</p>",
"5": "<p>&quot;If you will not listen to the words of my servants the prophets whom I keep sending to you urgently.&quot; The persistent-sending motif again (<em>hashkem</em>) — the long sequence of divine patience. Matthew 21:33-38 — the parable of the tenants who beat and killed the servants, then killed the son. Jesus identifies himself as the &quot;last messenger&quot; in a sequence of rejected prophets (Matt 23:35-37). The servants sent urgently in Jer 26:5 are the slaves beaten and killed in the parable; the son sent last is Christ himself.</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>&quot;I will make this house like Shiloh, and I will make this city a curse for all the nations on earth.&quot;</strong> Shiloh — where the tabernacle stood before the Philistines captured the ark (1 Sam 4) — is the prototype of divine presence withdrawn from a sanctuary. Jesus makes the same prophecy about the temple: Matthew 24:2 — &quot;not one stone here will be left on another; every one will be thrown down.&quot; John 2:19 — &quot;destroy this temple, and I will raise it in three days&quot; — he redirects the Shiloh-prophecy to his own body, the true temple that is destroyed and rebuilt. The house-like-Shiloh curse of Jer 26:6 is absorbed and transformed in Christ&apos;s resurrection.</p>",
"7": "<p>The priests, prophets, and all the people heard Jeremiah&apos;s words — the full religious establishment witnesses the sermon. The parallel at Jesus&apos;s temple-cleansing: Matthew 21:15 — &quot;the chief priests and the teachers of the law saw the wonderful things he did and the children shouting... and they were indignant.&quot; In both cases the full establishment is present; in both cases they respond with indignation and a plan for violence rather than repentance. The witness of the institutions is the witness that condemns itself.</p>",
"8": "<p>&quot;The priests, the prophets, and all the people seized him, saying: You must die!&quot; The mob arrest. Matthew 26:47-50 — &quot;while he was still speaking, Judas came, accompanied by a large crowd armed with swords and clubs.&quot; Mark 14:46 — &quot;the men seized Jesus and arrested him.&quot; The &quot;you must die&quot; verdict of the mob precedes and mirrors the &quot;he is worthy of death&quot; verdict of the council (Matt 26:66). Both Jeremiah and Jesus are seized by a religious mob after prophetic speech in/about the temple. The structural parallel is unmistakable.</p>",
"9": "<p>&quot;Why have you prophesied in the name of the LORD, saying that this temple will become like Shiloh?&quot; The charge: prophesying against the temple. Matthew 26:61 — &quot;this fellow said, &apos;I am able to destroy the temple of God and rebuild it in three days.&apos;&quot; Mark 14:58 — &quot;we heard him say, &apos;I will destroy this man-made temple and in three days will build another, not made by human hands.&apos;&quot; The false witnesses at Jesus&apos;s trial repurpose his temple-prophecy as the charge against him, exactly as Jeremiah&apos;s temple-sermon is the charge against him. The prophecy about the temple becomes the grounds for the prophet&apos;s death.</p>",
"10": "<p>The officials of Judah come up from the palace to the temple — the political establishment joins the religious mob. At Jesus&apos;s trial, the same combination: the chief priests and elders (religious establishment) combined with Pilate and the Roman officials (political establishment). Both trials involve the intersection of religious and political authority conspiring against the prophet. Acts 4:27 — &quot;both Herod and Pontius Pilate met together with the Gentiles and the people of Israel in this city to conspire against your holy servant Jesus.&quot;</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>&quot;This man deserves to die — he has prophesied against this city.&quot;</strong> The priests&apos; and prophets&apos; verdict: <em>mišpaṭ māwet</em> — a sentence of death. Matthew 26:66 — &quot;what do you think? He is worthy of death (<em>enochos thanatou</em>).&quot; The Sanhedrin&apos;s verdict on Jesus is the exact equivalent of the priests&apos; verdict on Jeremiah: the deserving-of-death charge for prophesying against the holy city. The accusation structure, the tribunal, and the verdict are parallel — Jeremiah&apos;s trial is the type; Jesus&apos;s trial is the antitype.</p>",
"12": "<p>&quot;The LORD sent me to prophesy against this house and this city all the words you have heard.&quot; Jeremiah&apos;s defense: divine commission. Jesus before the Sanhedrin: John 18:20-21 — &quot;I said nothing in secret. Why question me? Ask those who heard me.&quot; Before Pilate: John 18:36-37 — &quot;the reason I was born and came into the world is to testify to the truth.&quot; Both prophets ground their defense not in self-interest but in the truth of their divine commission. The messenger is not on trial for being a messenger; the message itself is what is at stake.</p>",
"13": "<p>&quot;Reform your ways and your deeds and obey the voice of the LORD your God, and the LORD will relent.&quot; The invitation to repentance embedded within the defense — Jeremiah does not merely seek acquittal but genuinely desires the repentance that would make his prophecies void. Acts 2:38 — Peter, in the shadow of the recently crucified Christ, issues the same invitation: &quot;repent and be baptized.&quot; Acts 3:19 — &quot;repent and turn to God, so that your sins may be wiped out, that times of refreshing may come from the Lord.&quot; The prophet who desires repentance rather than destruction is Christ incarnate.</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>&quot;As for me, I am in your hands. Do with me whatever you consider good and right.&quot;</strong> Jeremiah&apos;s surrender to the verdict. Isaiah 53:7 — &quot;he was oppressed and afflicted, yet he did not open his mouth; he was led like a lamb to the slaughter.&quot; John 18:11 — &quot;Shall I not drink the cup the Father has given me?&quot; John 19:11 — &quot;you would have no power over me if it were not given to you from above.&quot; Jeremiah&apos;s &quot;I am in your hands&quot; is the proto-passion moment — the prophet who submits himself to human judgment as the ultimate act of prophetic integrity. Christ&apos;s submission is identical in form and vastly deeper in content: he is actually innocent, and his submission is the atonement Jeremiah&apos;s only foreshadows.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>&quot;But know this for certain: if you put me to death, you will bring the guilt of innocent blood upon yourselves, upon this city, and upon its inhabitants.&quot;</strong> Innocent blood — <em>dam-nāqî</em>. Matthew 27:4 — Judas: &quot;I have sinned, for I have betrayed innocent blood (<em>haima athōon</em>).&quot; Matthew 27:24 — Pilate: &quot;I am innocent of this man&apos;s blood (<em>tou haimatos tou dikaiou toutou</em> — the blood of this righteous man).&quot; The &quot;innocent blood&quot; terminology of Jer 26:15 is used verbatim in the Passion narrative to describe the death of Christ — the evangelists are making a deliberate parallel to Jeremiah&apos;s trial. Christ&apos;s death brings the &quot;innocent blood&quot; guilt upon the city that Jeremiah warned about, and yet through his prayer (Luke 23:34 — &quot;Father, forgive them&quot;) he intercedes against the very guilt he warned of.</p>",
"16": "<p>&quot;This man does not deserve death — he has spoken to us in the name of the LORD our God.&quot; The officials&apos; acquittal of Jeremiah. The partial parallel to Pilate: John 18:38; 19:4, 6 — &quot;I find no basis for a charge against him&quot; (three times Pilate declares Jesus innocent). But the acquittals diverge in outcome: Jeremiah is released; Jesus is crucified despite Pilate&apos;s three-fold declaration of innocence. The acquittal that saves Jeremiah becomes the acquittal that the crowd overrides in Christ&apos;s case — his innocence is declared and then overridden by the mob&apos;s &quot;crucify him!&quot;</p>",
"17": "<p>The elders of the land who stand to give the precedent speech — the appeal to tradition in defense of prophetic speech. James 5:10 — &quot;brothers and sisters, as an example of patience in the face of suffering, take the prophets who spoke in the name of the Lord.&quot; The elders who invoke prophetic precedent to protect Jeremiah are doing what the NT writers do: reading the prophets&apos; suffering as the pattern that Christ fulfills and that his followers share. The precedent-speech of Jer 26:17 is the hermeneutical practice of reading prophetic history christologically.</p>",
"18": "<p>The elders cite Micah 3:12 — &quot;Zion will be plowed like a field, Jerusalem will become a heap of rubble.&quot; The use of one prophet to defend another — intertextual solidarity. Jesus invokes the same prophetic solidarity: Matthew 5:12 — &quot;in the same way they persecuted the prophets who were before you.&quot; Luke 24:44-45 — &quot;everything must be fulfilled that is written about me in the Law of Moses, the Prophets, and the Psalms.&quot; The prophets quote each other, fulfill each other, and ultimately all point to Christ as the prophet who summates and surpasses them all.</p>",
"19": "<p>&quot;Did Hezekiah put Micah to death? No — he feared the LORD and the LORD relented.&quot; Hezekiah as the positive precedent — the king who responds to prophetic warning with repentance. The contrast with Jehoiakim (who burns the scroll) and the contrast with those who killed Jesus is sharp. Hezekiah&apos;s fear of the LORD and seeking of divine favor (2 Kings 19:14-19) is the royal model that points toward Christ&apos;s own Gethsemane prayer — &quot;not my will but yours&quot; — as the ultimate example of reverent submission (Heb 5:7 — &quot;he was heard because of his reverent submission&quot;).</p>",
"20": "<p>Urijah son of Shemaiah — another prophet who prophesied the same message as Jeremiah against Jerusalem and the temple. The existence of multiple prophets with the same message is the interlinear confirmation of divine intention: two or three witnesses establish the word (Deut 19:15; Matt 18:16). Jesus himself notes the pattern: Matthew 23:37 — &quot;Jerusalem, Jerusalem, you who kill the prophets and stone those sent to you.&quot; Urijah is one more in this sequence of sent-and-killed prophets that runs from Abel (Matt 23:35) to Christ himself.</p>",
"21": "<p>King Jehoiakim sought to have Urijah executed — and Urijah fled to Egypt. The prophet who fled versus the prophet who stayed. Jeremiah stays; Christ stays in Jerusalem when he knows it means his death (Luke 13:33 — &quot;no prophet can die outside Jerusalem!&quot; — Jesus&apos;s self-conscious direction toward the city of his death). The contrast between Urijah&apos;s flight to Egypt and Jeremiah&apos;s remaining is the contrast Christ intensifies: he is the prophet who set his face like flint (Isa 50:7) and did not flee.</p>",
"22": "<p>Elnathan son of Achbor sent to Egypt to extradite Urijah — the king&apos;s long arm extending to Egypt. The irony is that Jeremiah would later be dragged to Egypt against his will (Jer 43), and Urijah is dragged from Egypt to Jerusalem. The prophets are controlled neither by geography nor by kings but by YHWH&apos;s purposes. Christ&apos;s own birth narrative included an Egypt-flight (Matt 2:14-15 — &quot;that it might be fulfilled: out of Egypt I called my son&quot;) that inverts Urijah&apos;s extradition and repeats the Exodus-pattern.</p>",
"23": "<p>&quot;They brought Urijah back from Egypt to King Jehoiakim, who had him executed. His body was thrown into the common burial ground.&quot; The prophet killed and dishonorably buried — the death of a servant cast aside. This is what they did to Christ in intention: the mockery, the crucifixion, the borrowed tomb. But the common burial of Urijah contrasts sharply with Isaiah 53:9 (&quot;his grave was assigned with the wicked&quot;) and its reversal (&quot;and with the rich in his death&quot; — he was buried in Joseph of Arimathea&apos;s new tomb). The prophet thrown into the common grave anticipates and contrasts with the prophet-king buried in a garden tomb and raised on the third day.</p>",
"24": "<p>&quot;But Ahikam son of Shaphan used his influence to protect Jeremiah, so that he was not handed over to the people to be executed.&quot; The hidden protector — the powerful official who uses his position to shelter the prophet. Joseph of Arimathea plays an identical role for Jesus: Mark 15:43-46 — &quot;a prominent member of the council, who was himself waiting for the kingdom of God, went boldly to Pilate and asked for Jesus&apos; body... Joseph bought some linen cloth, took down the body, wrapped it.&quot; Both Ahikam and Joseph are described as officials who use their influence for the dead/endangered prophet against the expected outcome of mob justice.</p>"
},
"27": {
"1": "<p>The reign of Zedekiah — the last king of Judah. Jeremiah&apos;s yoke-sign is performed for the king who will preside over Jerusalem&apos;s final destruction. The note about the dating &quot;in the beginning of the reign of Jehoiakim&quot; is acknowledged as a textual variant (the content refers to Zedekiah&apos;s reign); the MT textual note itself witnesses to the scribal care with which these prophecies were preserved. Christ fulfills the yoke-oracle under the ultimate last-king scenario: his crucifixion occurs under Roman rule, the end-state of the sequence of empires that Jeremiah&apos;s yoke-sign initiates.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>&quot;Make a yoke with its crossbars and straps, and put it on your neck.&quot;</strong> The yoke as sign-act — Jeremiah wearing Babylon&apos;s yoke on his body to symbolize the submission he advocates. Matthew 11:29-30 — &quot;take my yoke upon you and learn from me, for I am gentle and humble in heart, and you will find rest for your souls. For my yoke is easy and my burden is light.&quot; Christ speaks of a yoke that is the opposite of Babylon&apos;s: not the heavy yoke of foreign domination but the easy yoke of discipleship. Jeremiah&apos;s iron yoke becomes in Christ the yoke of love that does not crush but forms. The yoke-sign of Jer 27:2 finds its Christological answer in Matt 11:29.</p>",
"3": "<p>The message goes to the surrounding nations&apos; ambassadors through their envoys in Jerusalem — the international audience for the yoke-oracle. The apostolic mission has the same international reach: Acts 1:8 — &quot;you will be my witnesses in Jerusalem, and in all Judea and Samaria, and to the ends of the earth.&quot; The nations that Jeremiah addresses through their ambassadors are the nations that Christ&apos;s witnesses will reach directly. The diplomatic channel of Jer 27:3 becomes the missionary channel of the Great Commission.</p>",
"4": "<p>&quot;Give them this message for their masters: This is what the LORD of hosts, the God of Israel, says.&quot; The divine messenger formula to the foreign nations — YHWH of hosts (ṣĕbāʾôt) identifying himself as the God of Israel to the nations. John 17:3 — &quot;that they know you, the only true God, and Jesus Christ, whom you have sent.&quot; The knowledge of YHWH as Israel&apos;s God that Jeremiah broadcasts to the foreign kings is the knowledge that Christ broadcasts to all nations through the apostolic mission — only now it is the knowledge of the Father and the Son together.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>&quot;I made the earth — with the people and animals on it — by my great power and my outstretched arm, and I give it to whoever I please.&quot;</strong> The Creator&apos;s sovereign disposal of the earth. Matthew 28:18 — &quot;all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me.&quot; Jeremiah&apos;s YHWH exercises his authority by assigning the earth to Nebuchadnezzar; the risen Christ exercises all authority by commissioning his disciples to all nations. Both claims rest on the same creation-sovereignty: the Creator disposes of the earth as he wills. The &quot;outstretched arm&quot; of creation becomes the outstretched arms of the crucified one through whom authority is restored.</p>",
"6": "<p>&quot;Now I am giving all these lands into the hands of Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon, my servant.&quot; The transfer of authority to the divine servant — Nebuchadnezzar as ʿebed, servant. Philippians 2:7-8 — Christ &quot;emptied himself, by taking the form of a servant (<em>doulos</em>), being born in human likeness... he humbled himself by becoming obedient to the point of death.&quot; Isaiah 52:13 — &quot;See, my servant will act wisely.&quot; The divine servant-designation that Jeremiah applies to a pagan king becomes, in Isaiah&apos;s Servant Songs, the designation of the one who suffers vicariously and achieves what Babylon never could: genuine reconciliation.</p>",
"7": "<p>&quot;All the nations will serve him, and his son, and his grandson, until the time of his own land comes.&quot; The limited duration of Babylon&apos;s sovereignty — three generations, then the end. Daniel 7:13-14 — &quot;to him was given dominion and glory and a kingdom, that all peoples, nations, and languages should serve him; his dominion is an everlasting dominion, which shall not pass away.&quot; The kingdom given to the Son of Man in Daniel is the answer to the three-generation limitation of Jer 27:7 — Christ&apos;s kingdom does not pass to his son and grandson but is eternal, the only sovereignty without a &quot;time of its own land coming.&quot;</p>",
"8": "<p>&quot;If any nation or kingdom will not serve Nebuchadnezzar... I will punish that nation.&quot; The consequence of resisting the divinely appointed authority. Romans 13:1-2 — &quot;there is no authority except that which God has established... whoever rebels against the authority is rebelling against what God has instituted.&quot; Paul&apos;s counsel echoes Jeremiah&apos;s: submit to the authority God has permitted. But Christ transcends the logic: the authority he exercises (Matt 28:18) is ultimate, not delegated; those who submit to him are not merely avoiding punishment but entering life.</p>",
"9": "<p>&quot;Do not listen to your prophets, your diviners, your dreamers, your fortune-tellers, or your sorcerers, who tell you: You will not serve the king of Babylon.&quot; The false-prophets list — the comfortable lie of imperial exemption. Matthew 7:15 — &quot;watch out for false prophets. They come to you in sheep&apos;s clothing.&quot; Mark 13:22 — &quot;false messiahs and false prophets will appear and perform signs and wonders to deceive, if possible, even the elect.&quot; Christ gives the same warning against those who promise exemption from the real consequences of opposing God&apos;s purposes. The diviners of Jer 27:9 who promise no Babylonian yoke are the false Christs of Mark 13 who promise escape from the real coming judgment.</p>",
"10": "<p>&quot;They are prophesying a lie to you, and the result will be that you will be driven far from your land.&quot; The lie that produces the very outcome it denies. The paradox of false prophecy: those who say &quot;peace, peace&quot; produce the opposite of peace. Matthew 7:26-27 — &quot;everyone who hears these words of mine and does not put them into practice is like a foolish man who built his house on sand... it fell with a great crash.&quot; The false prophets of Jer 27:10 are the sand-foundation builders of Matt 7 — confidence in a false word produces the collapse it was supposed to prevent.</p>",
"11": "<p>&quot;But the nation that submits to the yoke of the king of Babylon and serves him — I will let it remain in its own land.&quot; The paradox of submission: humbling yourself under the divine-permitted authority leads to life; resisting leads to death. Matthew 11:28-30 — &quot;take my yoke upon you... and you will find rest for your souls.&quot; The yoke-submission of Jer 27:11 that preserves life is the exact pattern Christ uses for his own easy yoke. Submission to the divinely appointed burden (Babylon&apos;s yoke; Christ&apos;s yoke) is the path of life; resistance is the path of destruction.</p>",
"12": "<p>&quot;Submit to the king of Babylon&apos;s yoke, serve him and his people, and you will live.&quot; The live-or-die simplicity of the choice. John 10:10 — &quot;the thief comes only to steal and kill and destroy; I came that they may have life and have it abundantly.&quot; The life offered through submission in Jer 27:12 is the life offered through Christ in John 10 — but the conditions are inverted. Babylon offers life through political submission; Christ offers abundant life through death-and-resurrection, the ultimate paradox of the easy yoke.</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>&quot;Why should you and your people die by sword, famine, and plague, as the LORD has spoken against every nation that refuses to serve the king of Babylon?&quot;</strong> The divine desire that they not die. Ezekiel 18:31-32 — &quot;repent and live! Why will you die?&quot; 2 Peter 3:9 — &quot;the Lord... is patient with you, not wanting anyone to perish, but everyone to come to repentance.&quot; Christ&apos;s tears over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41) are the embodiment of this divine &quot;why should you die?&quot; — the grief that the avoidable death is chosen anyway. He does not want the death of any, yet he respects the freedom that chooses it.</p>",
"14": "<p>&quot;Do not listen to the prophets who tell you: You will not have to serve the king of Babylon.&quot; The reiterated warning against the comforting lie. 2 Timothy 4:3-4 — &quot;the time will come when people will not put up with sound doctrine... they will turn their ears away from the truth and turn aside to myths.&quot; The people of Jer 27:14 who listen to what they want to hear rather than what they need to hear are the people of 2 Tim 4:3 who accumulate teachers to suit their own desires. Christ is the teacher whose word cannot be adjusted to suit the listener (Matt 7:28-29 — he taught as one who had authority, not as their teachers of the law).</p>",
"15": "<p>&quot;I have not sent them, declares the LORD. They are prophesying falsely in my name.&quot; The divine disavowal of the false prophets. Matthew 7:22-23 — &quot;many will say to me on that day, &apos;Lord, Lord, did we not prophesy in your name...?&apos; Then I will tell them plainly, &apos;I never knew you. Away from me, you evildoers!&apos;&quot; Christ&apos;s disavowal of those who prophesied in his name but were not sent by him is the ultimate form of YHWH&apos;s &quot;I have not sent them.&quot; The criterion is not the name invoked but the commission received — and Christ knows who received it.</p>",
"16": "<p>&quot;Do not listen to your prophets who keep telling you that the vessels of the LORD&apos;s house will be returned from Babylon — for they are prophesying a lie to you.&quot; The false prophecy of imminent restoration — the comfortable timeline that makes no demands for repentance. Revelation 3:3 — &quot;if you do not wake up, I will come like a thief, and you will not know at what time I will come to you.&quot; The false prophets who give a comfortable immediate-restoration timeline are the counterpart of those in Revelation who are not watching. Christ does not promise comfortable timelines; he promises return on the Father&apos;s schedule (Matt 24:36 — &quot;no one knows about that day or hour, not even the angels in heaven, nor the Son, but only the Father&quot;).</p>",
"17": "<p>&quot;Do not listen to them. Serve the king of Babylon and live. Why let this city be made into a wasteland?&quot; Jeremiah&apos;s passionate appeal for pragmatic survival — serve and live. In Christ&apos;s logic, the paradox is complete: John 12:24-25 — &quot;unless a grain of wheat falls to the ground and dies, it remains only a single seed. But if it dies, it produces many seeds. Anyone who loves their life will lose it, while anyone who hates their life in this world will keep it for eternal life.&quot; The &quot;serve and live&quot; of Jer 27:17 becomes &quot;lose your life and find it&quot; (Matt 10:39) in Christ&apos;s upside-down economy.</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>&quot;But if they truly are prophets and if the word of the LORD is really with them, let them pray and intercede with the LORD of hosts, that the vessels which are left in the LORD&apos;s house, in the royal palace, and in Jerusalem should not be taken to Babylon.&quot;</strong> The test of a true prophet: intercessory prayer for preservation rather than comfortable prediction. Hebrews 7:25 — Christ &quot;always lives to make intercession for them.&quot; Romans 8:34 — &quot;Christ Jesus who died — more than that, who was raised to life — is at the right hand of God and is also interceding for us.&quot; The prophet-test of Jer 27:18 is answered definitively by Christ as the great intercessor who prays not merely for temple vessels but for the whole people (John 17:20 — &quot;I pray also for those who will believe in me through their message&quot;).</p>",
"19": "<p>The bronze pillars, the large basin, the movable stands — the temple furnishings that represent YHWH&apos;s covenant presence. Hebrews 9:1-5 describes these furnishings in the context of the old covenant worship that Christ supersedes: &quot;the first covenant had regulations for worship and also an earthly sanctuary.&quot; The specific articles that Jeremiah&apos;s oracle addresses (pillars, basin, stands) are the same categories Hebrews discusses as belonging to the old covenant order that Christ fulfills by his own body as the true temple (John 2:21 — &quot;the temple he had spoken of was his body&quot;).</p>",
"20": "<p>Nebuchadnezzar had not taken these particular vessels at the first deportation of Jeconiah (597 BC) — they remained for the final deportation. The incremental loss of the sacred objects across multiple deportations traces the staged withdrawal of covenant presence. Each deportation is a further step in the removal of the temple as the locus of divine dwelling. Christ&apos;s announcement that his body is the true temple (John 2:19-21) means the progressive loss of the physical temple-vessels is the context for the appearance of the indestructible temple — his resurrection body that death cannot permanently take away.</p>",
"21": "<p>&quot;This is what the LORD of hosts, the God of Israel, says about those vessels still in the LORD&apos;s temple, in the royal palace.&quot; The vessels &quot;still there&quot; — what remains after partial loss. The remnant-objects parallel the remnant-people: both will be taken to Babylon, both will be brought back. The remnant-logic of the vessels mirrors the remnant-theology of Isaiah and Paul. Christ as the ultimate remnant-embodiment (Isa 4:2-6 — &quot;the Branch of the LORD&quot; is the remnant&apos;s glory) is the one remaining object of ultimate value when all else has been taken to Babylon.</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>&quot;They will be taken to Babylon and remain there until the day when I attend to them, declares the LORD. Then I will bring them back and restore them to this place.&quot;</strong> The exile-and-return promise for the sacred vessels. Acts 3:21 — &quot;heaven must receive him until the time comes for God to restore everything, as he promised long ago through his holy prophets.&quot; The restoration of the temple vessels anticipated in Jer 27:22 points beyond Ezra&apos;s partial return (Ezra 1:7-11 — Cyrus restoring the vessels) to the ultimate restoration of all things that Christ will bring at his return. He is both the vessel taken away (Col 2:9 — all the fullness of deity in bodily form) and the one who brings back everything that was lost.</p>"
}
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'jeremiah')
    merge_comm(existing, JEREMIAH)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'jeremiah', existing)
    print('Jeremiah 25-27 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
